  "prompt": "What is the electron configuration of electron?",
  "response": "The electron configuration of a single electron, as seen in a hydrogen atom (the simplest atom), is simply \\(1s^1\\). This configuration indicates that the electron occupies the lowest energy level (the 1s orbital).\n\nIn more general terms, if you are referring to an isolated electron (without being in an atom), it does not have an electron configuration in the way we typically describe for electrons within atoms. An isolated electron is just a negatively charged particle without a specific arrangement or energy state associated with atoms. ",
